solution.p:
 In order to find where is f(x) increasing, we find where is f'(x) positive.
f'(x)=\frac{\frac{2x+4}{2\sqrt{x-1}}-2\sqrt{x-1}}{(2x+4)^2}=\frac{(x+2)-2(x-1)}{\sqrt{x-1}(2x+4)^2}
=\frac{-x+4}{\sqrt{x-1}(2x+4)^2}
The denominator is never negative, so  f(x) is increasing when the numerator of f'(x) is positive, i.e. when 4-x \gt 0, or x \lt 4. Recalling that the domain of definition for f(x) is [1,+\infty), we conclude that f(x) is increasing on the interval (1,4).
